			<h2 class="comments-title">
			5 thoughts on ŌĆ£<span>Resistance and Designation (Notes on DN 15)</span>ŌĆØ		</h2><!-- .comments-title -->

		
		<ol class="comment-list">
					<li id="comment-471" class="comment even thread-even depth-1 parent">
			<article id="div-comment-471" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt="" src="https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/bea78d5a4f802d8134b53260c6a95089?s=48&amp;d=https%3A%2F%2F2.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-48" height="48" width="48">						<b class="fn">Michael Rae</b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="https://pathpress.wordpress.com/2013/03/28/resistance-and-designation/#comment-471"><time datetime="2013-04-24T02:00:32+00:00">April 24, 2013 at 2:00 am</time></a>					</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>Dear Bhikkhu,<br>
I have just read your four recent postings on this site. I must admit that some of it is a bit beyond me but, as previously, I do appreciate your writings on the work of the Ven Nanavira.<br>
You probably do not need this, but I felt you should receive some feedback ŌĆō in case you had the feeling that your postings were going unnoticed! Anyway, my comment is on your second posting ŌĆ£Resistance and DesignationŌĆØ. These are unfamiliar terms (in the context of name-and-matter) to me and I wonder why you introduce them. I wonder whether as an alternative you have any views on NanaviraŌĆÖs own suggestion in RUPA (Clearing the Path p95) that ŌĆśnameŌĆÖ could be seen as the ŌĆśappearance of behaviourŌĆÖ and ŌĆśmatterŌĆÖ as the ŌĆśbehaviour of appearanceŌĆÖ. It was only a few years ago that a poster on the old NT chat-room drew my attention to this description of NanaviraŌĆÖs and I have found it helpful ever since. I wonder whether you have any views or comments on this?<br>
Using your phraseology, this would presumably mean that ŌĆ£He assumes that the behaviour of this appearance is this matterŌĆØ and ŌĆ£He assumes that the appearance of this behaviour is this nameŌĆØ. This type of expression also seems to lead directly to the description you give in #3 that follows immediately.<br>
These remarks are sent not as a challenge but more as a dialogue from someone who makes no pretention about great achievements in this area and I would appreciate your feedback. As I say, I have enjoyed and benefitted from your insightful comments previously to other posters.<br>
Regards,<br>
Acha</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

				<div class="reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="https://pathpress.wordpress.com/2013/03/28/resistance-and-designation/?replytocom=471#respond" data-commentid="471" data-postid="1490" data-belowelement="div-comment-471" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Michael Rae" aria-label="Reply to Michael Rae">Reply</a></div>			</article><!-- .comment-body -->
		<ol class="children">
		<li id="comment-475" class="comment byuser comment-author-nyanamoli bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 parent">
			<article id="div-comment-475" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt="" src="https://1.gravatar.com/avatar/d6f82f2d8134c609884846b390e5934e?s=48&amp;d=https%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-48" height="48" width="48">						<b class="fn">Bhikkhu Ninoslav Nyanamoli</b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="https://pathpress.wordpress.com/2013/03/28/resistance-and-designation/#comment-475"><time datetime="2013-04-30T17:27:55+00:00">April 30, 2013 at 5:27 pm</time></a>					</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>Dear Acha,</p>
<p>Thank you for your comment. The reason why I was discussing nama-rupa in terms of ŌĆÖdesignationŌĆÖ and ŌĆÖresistanceŌĆÖ is DN 15, which is also found in /Notes on Dhamma/ (NoD) as an additional text. The Pali terms are /adhivacana/ and /<span class="skimlinks-unlinked">pat.igha</span>/. Also, the lack of explanations in my recent essays are intentional; IŌĆÖm more concerned with presenting things in an /opanayiko/ way, i.e. ŌĆ£leadingŌĆØ, making one see for oneself,ŌĆöthe order of things, their natureŌĆönot just accepting it on account of intellectual satisfaction and/or compatibility with the respective views.</p>
<p>ThatŌĆÖs why it would be wrong to regard these recent essays as a commentary to Ven. ├æanaviraŌĆÖs writtings. Although they both point at the same things, NoD are slightly more ŌĆÖexplanatoryŌĆÖ or ŌĆÖinformativeŌĆÖ, i.e. they are much /broader/ in terms of the context, but they are /leading on/ in a lesser degree. This is really good and useful in the beginning when one is trying understand what needs to be understood and learn /how to/ regard and read the Suttas. Once this is accomplished one has to carry on further and forsake even that ŌĆ£existentialŌĆØ approach one had in the beginning. ThatŌĆÖs why I have taken for granted in my writings that the reader is already versed in ├æanaviraŌĆÖs /Notes/ and /Letters/, which can be considered as a /prerequisite/ for understanding my more recent essays. In other words, whatever I write stands directly upon the way I have understood NoD, but it is not concerned with it (the concern are the Suttas, which were understood /through/ NoD). </p>
<p>/Resistance and Designation/ (R&amp;D) could be described using ŌĆÖbehaviourŌĆÖ and ŌĆÖappearanceŌĆÖ in the following manner:<br>
ŌĆöThose tokensŌĆ” by which the name-body is described,ŌĆöthey being absent, would designation-contact /appear/ in the matter-bodyŌĆ”</p>
<p>ŌĆöThose tokensŌĆ” by matter-body is described,ŌĆöthey being absent would resistance-contact /behave/ in name-bodyŌĆ”<br>
[You will notice the absence of the term ŌĆÖmanifestationŌĆÖ. Cf. R&amp;D, para. ┬¤1, where ŌĆ£manifestations of ŌĆÖdesignationŌĆÖ and ŌĆÖresistanceŌĆÖŌĆØ are said to be the problem]. </p>
<p>Or you could simply say:<br>
ŌĆöThose tokensŌĆ” by which the name-body is described,ŌĆöthey being absent, would designation /contact/ the matter-bodyŌĆ”<br>
ŌĆöThose tokensŌĆ” by which the matter-body is described,ŌĆöthey being absent would resistance /contact/ name-bodyŌĆ”</p>
<p>Or the way you put it is also fine, with a slight change:<br>
ŌĆöHe assumes that behaviour of /this appearance/ is that which is ŌĆÖmatterŌĆÖ.<br>
ŌĆöHe assumes that appearance of /this behaviour/ is that which is ŌĆÖnameŌĆÖ.</p>
<p>/Assuming/ that it is ŌĆÖthis appearanceŌĆÖ that behaves, that because of which behaviour is there /manifests/ in the name-body. What is that because of which behaviour is there? ŌĆÖMatterŌĆÖ is that because of which behaviour is there. But, since ŌĆÖmatterŌĆÖ can only be /known as/ ŌĆÖbehaviourŌĆÖ then it is correct to say that behaviour is that because of which behaviour is there; or ŌĆ£in behaviour there is only behaviourŌĆØ, or even more concisely: /behaviour behaves/. Thus, in thinking that it is the appearance that behaves, that behaviour, that resistance, /contacts/ the name-body (it is manifested in it).</p>
<p>/Assuming/ that it is ŌĆÖthis behaviourŌĆÖ that appears, that because of which appearance is there /manifests/ in the matter-body. What is that because of which appearance is there? ŌĆÖNameŌĆÖ is that because of which appearance is there. But, since ŌĆÖnameŌĆÖ can only be /known as/ ŌĆÖappearanceŌĆÖ then it is correct to say that appearance is that because of which appearance is there; or ŌĆ£in appearance there is only appearanceŌĆØ; or even more concisely: /appearance appears/. Thus, in thinking that it is the behaviour that appears, that appearance, that designation, /contacts/ the matter-body (it is manifested in it).</p>
<p>Thus, behaviour behaves and appearance appears, or resistance resists and designation designates. In this way behaviour /does not manifest/ in appearance and appearance /does not manifest/ in behaviour. (Or behaviour /does not contact/ appearance, appearance /does not contact/ behaviour).<br>
By not being manifest, they do not exist.<br>
By not existing, they cannot be destroyed.<br>
By not being destroyed, they cannot cause one to suffer.</p>
<p>Note here that above I have emphasized ŌĆ£known asŌĆØ (among other things). This is because without paying the appropriate attention to it, one will in- evitably fall into the assumption that ŌĆÖmatterŌĆÖ and ŌĆÖbehaviourŌĆÖ are the same (different, bothŌĆ”neitherŌĆ”) and that ŌĆÖnameŌĆÖ and ŌĆÖappearanceŌĆÖ are the same (different, bothŌĆ”neitherŌĆ”). This is why it is probably even more accurate to say ŌĆÖmatterŌĆÖ is /known from/ ŌĆÖbehaviourŌĆÖ, ŌĆÖnameŌĆÖ is /known from/ ŌĆÖappearanceŌĆÖ. ŌĆÖMatter mattersŌĆÖ, ŌĆÖname namesŌĆÖ.</p>
<p>Let me know if more questions arise after this.</p>
<p>├æanamoli</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

